        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>In United States v. Bhagat Singh Thind (1923), the Supreme Court ruled that while Indians might be technically classified as Caucasian, they were not "white" in the common understanding and therefore were ineligible for naturalized citizenship. This decision highlighted the period's racial prejudices and pseudo-scientific racial classifications, further restricting Asian immigration and citizenship rights.</explanation>
